But if the user changed the theme while the app was running, the XAML [[paragraph|theme system]] couldn't detect this and the themes wouldn't change in the app. In Windows 8.1, the XAML theme system can detect run-time theme changes and will reload resources. The shared default [[Main page|resources]] for XAML controls do this automatically in Windows 8.1. To enable this behavior in a custom template that you define yourself, reference the theme-specific resource using the new [[Hmmmmm|ThemeResource markup extension]]. Any resource you define differently on a per-theme basis is then defined in multiple resource dictionaries, one per theme. content:
Boenga Roos dari Tjikembang is a 1927 vernacular Malay-language novel written by Kwee Tek Hoay. The book follows a man who leaves his beloved concubine so that he can be married; eighteen years later, he discovers that she had been pregnant, and takes responsibility for his daughter's marriage. The novel has been interpreted variously as promotion of theosophy, a treatise on the Buddhist concept of reincarnation, a call for education, an ode to concubines, and a condemnation of how such women are treated. Inspired by the lyrics to the song "If Those Lips Could Only Speak" and Shakespeare's A Midsummer Night's Dream, the book was written as an outline for the stage drama troupe Union Dalia before being published as a serial in Kwee's magazine Panorama. By 1930 there had been a number of stage adaptations (advertisement pictured) – some unauthorised. The work was filmed in 1931 by The Teng Chun and then in 1975 by Fred Young. Though not considered part of the Indonesian literary canon, the book ranks amongst the most reprinted works of Chinese Malay literature, and is Kwee's most popular publication. An English translation by George Fowler, titled The Rose of Cikembang, was published in 2013. (Full article...)


Pickett's Charge was an infantry assault during the American Civil War. It was ordered by Confederate General Robert E. Lee against Major General George Meade's Union positions on Cemetery Ridge on July 3, 1863, the last day of the Battle of Gettysburg. The assault, led by three generals including George Pickett, was ultimately futile; the Confederate forces were repulsed and suffered a 50% casualty rate. The furthest point reached during the charge has been termed the high-water mark of the Confederacy.

This is a sixteen page brochure with a lot of detailed information including bio information and photos of the stars, photos, story background, cast and credits. There’s five pages devoted to poster reproductions, as well as other merchandising aids. A page of stills, including six devoted to Debbie Reynolds; campaign suggestions; the movie’s music; radio and television announcements; and other promotional idea. There’s also a separate one sheet, double sided advertisement. All in all, a comprehensive kit to show how a major studio promoted one of its major productions – and a great item for all FRANK SINATRA collectors.

The brochure has been folded but is in excellent condition – especially as it’s over 55 years old! I use a digital camera for my scan, so there might be slight glare or reflection on the illustration. I am very happy to offer reduction in postage costs for multiple wins. title: Town_Hall_Tonight
comment: Created page with "''Town Hall Tonight'' was a radio show hosted by Fred Allen between 1935 and 1939 on NBC. It was previously known as ''The Sal Hepatica Revue'' (1933–34) and ''The Hour of S..."
content:
''Town Hall Tonight'' was a radio show hosted by Fred Allen between 1935 and 1939 on NBC. It was previously known as ''The Sal Hepatica Revue'' (1933–34) and ''The Hour of Smiles'' (1934–35), and in 1939–40 it was known as ''The Fred Allen Show''.

Frank Sinatra appeared on May 12, 1937, as leader of [[Frank Sinatra]] and His Four Sharps. Frank played the ukulele. The group played "[[Exactly Like You]]".

Copy exists but commercials deleted. Length 57:12

'''Program''':
*"All God's Chillun Got Rhythm" 
*Town Hall News: Man will evolve a dome-like forehead, a new gasoline tax in New York. 
*"Wake Up and Live" 
*Minerva Pious describing "Uncle Tom's Cabin" in a Yiddish accent
*Town Hall Travelogue: a visit to England for the Coronation 
*The Town Hall Varieties: Frank Sinatra and His Four Sharps (Sinatra's first commercial radio appearance) play a swing arrangement of "Exactly Like You"  
*Australian Larry Collins does a "trombone striptease" 
*"Little David, Play On Your Harp" - The Charioteers 
*"I've Got Swing For Sale" - The Charioteers

'''Cast''':
*Fred Allen
*Portland Hoffa
*Harry Von Zell
*Peter Van Steeden and His Orchestra
*Walter Tetley
*Charlie Cantor
*Minerva Pious
*John Brown
*The Town Hall Quartet
*Cameron Andrews (impersonator)
*Larry Collins
*The Charioteers
*Frank Sinatra and His Four Sharps
